author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
He sighs. Does he expect someone to hear him? No one is around. He must be DESPERATE for attention. Most places where criminals are incarcerated are segregated by gender, so that removes his one and only hobby. Poor guy. Haha.

The sigh is a little too exaggerated and accompanied by bodily movement, however. His wound stings and he grimaces.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
A guard walks by. Zaquera glances at him. He was once quite nervous every time this happened, but it’s become routine enough that he’s gotten over it.

Everything is routine. He wakes up. He’s given food. He’s granted time in a more open area. He goes to sleep. In some regard it is a comfort.

Someone else trails behind the guard, though, which is less common.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
The guard opens Zaquera’s cell. He gets up, anticipating that he’s going to be asked to do something, interrogated or forced to perform manual labor as some sort of lesson. But all that happens is they direct the person accompanying them into the cell.

Zaquera tenses up. He was already uncomfortable being in close isolated contact with unfamiliar people before all of this. “…What is this? Who are you?” He says, trying very hard to avoid stuttering pathetically.

author.name: scipe

messages.content: “I’m The Culprit.” The Culprit says.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“What?” Zaquera stares blankly ahead. That’s not a fucking name.

“It’s not a fucking name, I know. Don’t worry about it.” The Culprit rolls his(?) eyes.

“What?” Zaquera says what again.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“Look, there was this whole plotline that was abandoned, and…” He shakes his head. “It doesn’t matter. I’m here for being ‘important’ to some nonsense, and easier to lock up than deal with in some other way. Same as you. Same as Rikarasu. I think. Haven’t exactly seen her.”

“So she is here…” Zaquera mutters.

“She was, at least. I’m not sure if she’s been transferred back. I’m not personally in charge of the plans about that.” The Culprit shrugs.

“Transferred…?” Zaquera’s eyebrows furrow in confusion before realizing that word can mean something else. “To a different facility.”

“No, your initial assumption was right.” The Culprit, practically a mind-reader right now.

“What? No. The Antarctica Project is over. I literally cannot perpetuate it. Unless Dextrum is messing about again, but I don’t think he’d have enough control…” Zaquera puts a hand to his chin, lost in thought.

“You need to think a little more outside the box, man.” The Culprit chuckles darkly. “Hasn’t it felt like there was someone else pulling the strings? Someone beyond you and your bestie OC?”

“…You?” Zaquera stares at The Culprit.

“Only metaphorically. I’ve just been given access to some info.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“Information such as…? Who even are you, really? Surely I’m in no situation where knowing your identity could matter remotely.”

“I already told you.” He dismisses it. “And the information is stuff like…” He leans in close.

“I watched Sheeval die.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“W-What?!” Zaquera sweats.

“Yup.”

“How could you have… that’s… stop trying to mess with me.” Culbasko calms himself down a bit.

“I mean, again, not quite personally. But I know the guy who did pretty well.”

“You know the culprit? Or. You’re… by the culprit, I mean—”

“I know what you mean, yeah.” He nods. “It was some nineteenth century English author, they don’t really matter.”

“What?” Zaquera continues to blankly say ‘what’. It seems he has no value left. Once he stops being the one who knows and exposits the information, there’s nothing left of him.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“The part that matters is…” The Culprit leans in close again. “He let me do it.”

“That… so it *was* you…” Zaquera stammers. 

“Again, only metaphorically. I’m just speaking from that person’s perspective out of convenience.” The Culprit smiles. “He would rather die painfully than keep living with what he’d done. With what *you* made him do.”

“…That isn’t true. Deltent… he was wracked by guilt, that much is certain. But he always believed in atoning by continuing to live and trying to do good.”

“Yeah, well, I guess that good only stretched as far as the start of the project. Or I was just really convincing. I gotta tell you, the setup was seriously clever. Having the victim cooperate allows for murder tricks that are beyond compare. Viotto would’ve been in deep shit to avoid the frame job if he didn’t just manage to sidestep all that entirely.”

“That’s — what the fuck is wrong with you? Why would you do this?!” Zaquera speaks weakly, disturbed.

“It’s not me, dummy. But the answer is simple.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“I want people like you to suffer.”

“…You’re lying.” Zaquera spits.

“No, I really do. I fucking hate—”

“Not about that. About Sheeval. He wouldn’t do that. That’s not the type of man he is.” Zaquera shakes his head.

“Well, I guess you didn’t know him that well.” The Culprit shrugs.

“I did.”

“You didn’t.”

“Yes, I did.”

“No.”

“Yes.”

“No.”

“Yes.”

“Whatever.” The Culprit yawns.

“Are you here to kill me, then?” Zaquera mutters, disinterested. “This isn’t exactly subtle.”

“Hmmmmmm.” The Culprit pretends to contemplate this.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“You know, it wasn’t satisfying. Sheeval dying. The whole revenge thing — it’s not doing it for me. The closure there doesn’t scratch much of an itch.”

“Revenge… so you believe you’ve been wronged by me? By him, as well… Then, by the project?” Zaquera inquires. “Before you do this… Who exactly are you?”

“Buddy, I ask myself the same question every fucking day.” The Culprit rushes in close… and pats Zaquera on the back.

“Eh????” He stares dumbfounded.

“Why would I give you that? You’re nothing, Zaquera. You split your work among those more competent than you. Your role is split in half with another guy. You ceded every chance you had at a legacy by never being a father once, despite fathering countless. Which, like, by the way, what the fuck is up with that? Is not wanting to use protection, like, a tactile thing? Do you have a fetish for—” The Culprit stops himself, holding his head.

“What.” Zaquera.

“Nothing, forget it. The point is that you’re boring. You don’t get to mind hack me into shooting you and then say some cryptic shit in Latin. You don’t get to have your grand motives revealed at the very end. You don’t get to secretly be dead the whole time. You don’t get to have John Leiblich climb to the top of the building, following a planned outcome you crafted, and shoot you, causing you to fall out the window in a glorious act of narratively potent suicide. You don’t get *anything*. Your end is here, in this fucking room, rotting away.”

“…Then why are you here?” Zaquera asks.

The Culprit smiles.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
The Culprit gestures vaguely behind them. “Do you recognize that guard?”

“…No?”

“Figures. Well, it’s another person whose family you tore apart. Maybe you fucked his wife? Maybe he’s the father of the DeChais. Honestly, we’ve gotten so into conversations about just setting up this meeting that I kind of forget who he fucking is. He has reason to hate you, is the point.”

Zaquera looks up at the guard, still standing just outside the cell. “So… he is the man I will meet my end by?”

“…Nah. Though a tertiary character whose name isn’t even made clear… that *would* be pretty funny.” The Culprit smirks. “I lied to them.” He whispers to Zaquera.

“…Hm?”

“He still hates you, I couldn’t dissuade him from that, but using insider knowledge, I made him believe I was also culpable for his suffering.”

“What? Why would you do that? Why are you here, none of this makes…” Zaquera squints. That obviously doesn’t make sense for someone to do.

The Culprit shrugs. “I dunno. I guess I wanted to see your face. Your reaction when you’re denied a cathartic death of being blamed for your sins. More broadly, why I’m here… it’s to tie up loose ends.” The Culprit takes a deep breath.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
“…Loose ends. But not me. Killing me, at least.” Zaquera confirms he understands.

“Yeah.” The Culprit nods. “I’m the only one left, out of the five. The online account was a special case, and Eric went rogue, but me… I’ve just never had the chance. It’s time.”

Zaquera obviously barely fucking understands what is being said here. “Ah.” He feigns being marginally less ignorant. He’s tired. This conversation isn’t ever going to give him anything. Just more people who despise him, more people impossible to have a conversation with.

The Culprit stands up straight. “You know, pestilence isn’t even real.”

“Hm?” Zaquera stares, unable to disguise his confusion this time. “…Pestilence?”

“It’s not one of the four. That was just made up later. Because it sounds cooler? I guess?” The Culprit shakes his head and turns around.

“What are you talking about?” Zaquera asks.

He doesn’t receive clarification.

messages.content:
Catarina Praxis, also known by some as "Neko", raises her fist high into the air. She's finished another of her endless speeches, her constant pleas for attention or strategic securing of support depending on what you want to call it. 

The crowd cheers.

Some of her long time supporters are there with her up on the platform. Off to the side, not placed in any central position but certainly visible, is strange micro-celebrity and noteworthy historical entity "Intuition Overdrive". Probably? Looks a bit different. Hair grown out a bit, probably. Dressing differently from usual. Like a... well, y'know.

The proceedings wrap up. It doesn't really matter what exactly she was saying to those people. It never does.

In a room that can be loosely quantifiable as 'backstage', Neko retreats and shuts the door behind her. She lets out a deep breath. Also here are the aforementioned Intuition Overdrive, and, for some fucking reason, a young lad named Wozniak Dreng.

"Yes, don't get ahead of yourself." Neko chuckles uncomfortably.

"I'm just tryna be respectful. See--" Eren's next words are inaudible, as loud booing is heard in her presence.

"Where the hell are you...?" Neko mutters.

"I'm making political connections! Meeting covertly, in a public place, that's how you do it, you know...!" Eren screams, not at all covert. She turns the camera to a rather shady looking man gazing intently ahead, not at the camera. "Mince, say hi. Mince. Hey." Eren's voice is audible. Mince McVahon, an incredibly real character, is unshaken, and does not move his gaze away from the spectacle in front of him. Eren gives up and returns the focus to herself.

"How public are you talking? What is going on...?" Neko.

"It's a sports match. What's going on... Uhhh, so, there's the big man, as usual, and then a new guy whose gimmick seems to entirely be being evil, which they all really hate, or like, in sort of the bad guy way --"

"Eren, I don't care. Please move somewhere quieter." Neko shakes her head, having no appreciation for the fine art of wrestling.

"Okay!" Eren smiles and acquiesces, spending several minutes doing nothing but walking, showing no respect for all our time.

Eren finally makes her way over to somewhere less insufferably loud. "Okay! So. He's in. It's gonna be him."

Catarina holds her head. "It's been a bit since I had to worry about things back home. Too busy with a place where the politics aren't ridiculous. Who's in? You said you were still considering different options."

"Atlas Cruz." Eren says this name.

"...Come on." Catarina groans.

"I knoooow you have your misgivings. But he's a war hero! He's an icon among bureaucrats. He's got the best chance of anyone to beat Dextrum for the presidency, now that the whole interim power pretense is finally crumbling." Eren says this completely non-insane set of sentences.

"So? I don't care. How is he any better? I was trying to push *you* to run, frankly."

Eren scoffs. "I'd never win in a democracy. Look, queen--"

"Don't call me that." Neko mutters uncomfortably.

"Miss Neko, or whatever... it *will* be me, alright? Atlas doesn't believe in anything, not really. He's a shell of a person. The only thing that can fill that void in power is my ideals."

"What." Neko squints in disgust.

"And I'm loyal to you, of course." Eren smirks. "Just trust me, okay? I can handle things on this end. All I need is for you to act when the time is right."

"..." Neko contemplates this.

"When things in the desert go haywire... well, we'll see. Okay, I have to get back to attempting to have a conversation. Byyyyeeee, Neko. And you, the other guy?" She finally addresses Intuition, who has never stopped being here in the midst of all this inane conversation.

As my consciousness fades back in, I notice some odd things. My position, for one... I would never sleep sitting down like this. Then, the quality of the air surrounding me. And finally, the light piercing through my eyelids... this is not where I was, and certainly not where I'm meant to be. Could it be... happening again? Could I be back in?
I slowly open my eyes, ready to see some medieval-style setting, a room made of sandstone, anything along those lines. Instead, I get a relatively normal-looking enclosure. And... somebody that I recognize. I don't remember his name, but I remember his presence, at the close of what I consider the worst segment of my life thus far. It's not a pleasant thing to wake up to.

I sit up carefully, and look over at him. "T-tell me. Where are we, right now? Am I the only one who's been left in the dark here, yet again?"

I raise an eyebrow. Honestly. I’m not sure what I expected this reunion to entail, but Viotto definitely wasn’t it, and I’m certainly not a fan of this turn of events. What’s he thinking, exactly, inviting Viotto here...?

It doesn’t matter. I think I’m.. I think I’m just excited to see him soon, in whatever capacity that’ll be. I can wait for it. Even if it means tolerating Viotto.

...I might also be afraid. Of what this entails, or means, by any metric. I don’t know what I’m going to say to him when the time comes. Hopefully not more incoherent babbling.

But I can admit it to myself now, which is something I definitely was not previously doing. That what came before was excessively, um. Stupid and inexperienced fumbling, on my part. Shambling around in a dark room looking for a lightswitch, another example of me seeing a reflection and thinking it stars. 

Does it help that I now have a better perspective of where things went wrong? Will that actually alter my behavior at all? I’m not sure.

“Tunisia.” My lip curls. “You may have heard of it. Or not. I’m not sure how senile you are yet. Haha.”

I do have some doubts as to why that would be where we're required for whatever plan we might be involved in, but I'll take you at your word on that one, for now. Nonetheless, it's not a satisfactory answer to my question. We aren't in a country, we're in a room. Have you ever been lost and thought to yourself, well, I don't know what street I'm on, but at least I know which country this is? Has that ever been a reassurance to you? People don't broadly categorize themselves like that. Unless, of course, you believe yourself to exist in a world of only generalized truths, one where individual actions carry as little meaning as the boundary to a piece of land. Is that the case? Hm?"

I don't expect a thorough response. This person clearly holds me in contempt, and this is more of a method to judge how they operate under clear moral pressure than it is an attempt to start up a friendly exchange. Still, I look at them pointedly.

What the fresh hell is he talking about? More of something incoherent, no doubt, which is what I’ve come to expect from him, but it’s still off-putting. I sidestep the issue of his unsubtle probing for the time being.

“Tunis.” I shift my head to the side. “The capital of Tunisia. Some sort of conference room, I’d wager. I don’t know what a satisfactory answer would look like to you, but this is what you’re getting.”

A moment.

“...How much do you remember, old man?” It’s mocking. I’m not sure what my intent is here, even going in. There’s no, um.. No concerted plan, for this sort of thing. Other than wanting to hear his answer.

messages.content:
Fine. "I remember everything. If you mean about The Antarctica Project, then I assume you also believe that it's related to my sudden departure from where I'm meant to be. And if you mean about yourself, then I remember as much as I ever knew, which is next to nothing. I know that you believe there to be no distinction between the body and the soul, of course, and from that I can gather some moral leanings you might exhibit, but I am not one to be prejudicial in advance. For now, we should approach this as a blank slate situation. Don't you agree? I will play my part as the weary old man, and you will do what you can to assist with that. And at the moment, the assistance you can provide is explaining why you have any knowledge of this situation, when I do not. Doesn't that seem fair, as my potential kidnapper?"

There is another man in this room, of course, but I simply have no reason to suspect him of anything. He receives a presumption of indirect involvement while he remains silent.

messages.content:
I take that drivel bordering on hysteria to mean that the identity Rowan has fallen completely by the wayside, at least for now. The thought brings me no small amount of relief, in spite of that personality being initially tailored to Viotto’s, ergh, tastes (and thus rendering him somewhat less intolerable to talk to.) 

The water’s under the bridge. The lack of pretense is affirming, exciting. No more garish gesturing towards complacency or submissiveness or whatever. Thank fuck. 

“I was invited.” I say shortly. “I’m guessing you were too, and you declined, which led to you being kidnapped and hoisted around like a sack of potatoes. Really, none of this would’ve happened if you were more *agreeable*, sir.” I smile.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\af114b26c161ebe1376c2e8061cbd7d4-EDAEE.png

messages.content:
"I did no such thing. The idea that I would decline such an invitation is, honestly, laughable. It may seem to you as though I lack self-awareness, son, but if I know one thing about myself, it is that I would not pass on the opportunity to humor somebody who was interested in my presence. It is, in fact, the ideal scenario to me. But where I am called into question, it gives an opportunity for reflection, no? You accuse me of disagreeableness, as if it is some sin to you. And even on your shallow premise, I must ask, when have you ever gone out of your way to show deference to me? Or to anyone else, for that matter? No, what you want is not a change in demeanor, or even polite dishonesty. What you wish for is a position of power, a swapping of roles, as they say. In your failure to recognize the inherent quality of reciprocal hierarchy, you have lost sight of what we are here for, perhaps... unless you never knew it in the first place?"

I leave that question open.

"Regardless, the fact that you came here with any foreknowledge is worrying. After all, you hardly seemed concerned with the idea that unwilling participants would have been brought here forcefully. In which case, it is easy to assume that you expected this level of violation of autonomy from our captors... and you came nonetheless, and here you sit, unconcerned for your own future. Forgive me for the directness, but if I am to believe that you are a participant in peerage to me, is this an attempt at outsourced self-harm? Such is the conclusion that any bystander would come to. And I'd like to believe that I am not in the company of those existing on that edge, that psychological vanishing point. You must be careful of the mental company you keep."

I pause to consider the prior sentence.

"To be clear, I say that not as an expression of concern for myself, but as one for you."

Why default to using our old, abandoned tablets as evidence... why speak of the manufactured messiah, Ovan... and, sincerely, why are you here with me? However, there is so far a key lack of the defensiveness that is idiosyncratic to this sort of individual - whether this is due to a lack of circumstance calling for it, or simply that this is the wrong conclusion to draw, is to be seen. That is one of the easier things to test for, however, and doing so shouldn't cut off any avenue of further discussion. But I need to consider the other main possibility here, of course: that I have been confronted with somebody who truly believes that they have found escape from their own personhood, that they have cast aside the shackles of the soul and been reborn multiple times in their own, sick identitarian baptism. There is a danger here... if I confront the untethered with what they see as the thing that tied them down, the 'truth', as it were, they may be unwilling to engage further. It is a trap I stumbled into one too many times in recent memory, although I maintain that it would have been difficult to avoid in many of the circumstances I was put into. Regardless, this is exacerbated by her supposed 'lofty ideals'... without any insight into what those might be, feigned or not, it is hard to place myself as opposed to or in line with them, to the point that I may unfortunately end up in a position that cannot be satisfactorily classified as either, the worst position to be in. But there is one angle here that avoids that pitfall, while also accomplishing the prior-stated test. And that hesitation I heard was real. I have no doubt.

"You, Verl... you value his opinion? And, to be clear, you do so 'not as a strawman'? I commend you for your principles there. It is good to not flatten people down, to not see them as paper cutouts. But I have a question. Why did you start from the position you did?"

She's lost track of functional human communication. It's not something that can be addressed with a simple back-and-forth... at least, not from somebody outside of her trusted inner circle. Is this 'Avdol' part of that? I can gamble on it. I follow through on the motion of the angled chair, tumble off of its side dramatically, and fall painfully to the ground, genuinely hurting my hip. I suck in a breath through my teeth.

"Ggghhhh!! Why... why have you done this to me?? All I wanted was to prevent you from potentially fracturing your relationship with that poor man... I did nothing to you! I forced nothing on you, and yet you only find violence in your heart! You... Avdol... is this truly the woman you have sought to defend...? Is this what you want, as well...? Disgusting... disgusting...!"

I writhe around a bit.

The scandals imminent to its wake have faded away. There is no intrinsic significance to the several people who played a role in it, when it comes to the lives of those normal folk throughout our nation.”

messages.content:
The conversation has, fortunately or unfortunately, moved on from me. I shift around slowly until I'm back on my feet, and lower myself back into the chair, hopefully without drawing much attention. My hip is still in pain, but not enough that I believe it to be a permanent issue, even at my age. But... this all makes me think. I do sympathize with this 'Verl', on some level. Politicians... they are so quick to move on from anything that can't be fit into some box, of 'scandal' or 'push' or 'campaign'. The people they are responsible for, the rote workers, are quite a different matter; but there is a certain dissociation that comes from this bureaucracy - I have seen it. Could we find common ground here? I have difficulties truly believing that, but there seem to be no other paths to pursue. Avdol is unable to commit to anything, that much is clear. Theseus... well, Theseus has failed. He did not take the opportunity I provided. Not a lost cause, of course, but clearly a subset of swaying Verl. It's too bad. He had so much promise, even at his young age.

"...Yes, Avdol. To discard the intrinsic significance of the participants... is it not the same as ignoring the intrinsic worth of any human? To believe that the common folk of your country have no investment in it is to say that they care for nobody, for nothing. Do you preside over a nation of nihilists? Or, perhaps, do they simply not believe that people can influence others in the world? Even if you have no faith in the significance of what we have accomplished here... surely, you must at least acknowledge that. If I were to..."

messages.content:
I blink, pushing briefly off the side of the wall to look at Avdol, at Verl’s urging. His distinctly pathetic face, steadfastly turned away from my direction.

...I’m surprised she remembered. Which is a callous thing to think, and I immediately internally grimace at it, but it’s still. There’s something there, to be sure. At the time he had been so uninterested in the proceedings that it, what?? Sparked a weird mental breakdown and subsequent identity crisis that I’m still kind-of sort-of in-recovery from? 

Okay, wait, I can’t allow myself to define my reaction only in terms of what ~~Be~~ *Verl* did to me. Or didn’t do! The whole point was that it wasn’t anything, literally *nothing* happened or occurred, so why...? Should I not just focus on the actual material harm? I turn to Avdol and mentally implore him to look at me.

“..That’s right.” I eventually say. “We’ve met before. And not under the best circumstances. Haha.” I smile without humor. “Say, was it the hair that made you so convinced I was a girl...? I did go out of my way to cut it afterwards.”

messages.content:
It’s funny, the ways combat differs between Earth and Arctica. It’s not entirely clear by this point how these mechanics work. At what point were a distinct set of rules entered? Was it when Verl worked up the resolve to take a life? When her associate did? Perhaps it’s impossible to pinpoint. The main takeaway is that the means by which physical violence is enacted much of the time in Arctica is completely absurd. Entire conversations can be had mid-sword-swing. It’s just the way of the world. In contrast, no such thing is possible on Earth. Lives are spared or taken instantaneously. A blunt pellet of lead shatters a human’s skull too quickly for anyone to even perceive it, for anything but an unrecognizable and unsightly lump of flesh in the aftermath to receive a reaction.

Both feel wrong, somehow. Both are just too much. Too sluggish, too jarring. Maybe there’s some middle ground that would feel a little less weird. Or maybe this topic matter will never quite feel ‘right’.

At any rate, Mohammad Avdol is dead now.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\76f49d11f9160bac20c987b4dbc5c23a-F34F2.png

messages.content:
I instinctively flinch at the sound of the gun firing, although over the last few minutes I had realized what was going to happen. Avdol’s face caves in on itself in an instant. What used to be a brain splatters against the back wall. His body slumps uselessly down, still half-restrained by vines, as the sludge of his face drips onto his nice carpet.

Ah. This must have been in the works for a while, then.

I’ve been around death for years at this point, but there’s still something immediately sobering about watching someone’s entire head reduced to a crater. I cover my face so as not to gag. I look to Verl to gauge her expression, to provide... comfort? I don’t know. Does she need that?

messages.content:
I start panicking. If he's disposable, everyone here is, I am! She could turn that gun on me whenever she wants! I have to get out of here, and none of this is remotely important to me. Right? I can just leave these people behind whenever I desire. This part of my life is over, I've already managed being back in my chosen existence. It was a series of disconnected attempts at fulfillment that led nowhere and expounded upon nothing, and I don't need to be stuck in a room with the fading remnants of the things gesturing back to it, not when it's putting my life at risk. That's not the kind of attachment I have. It isn't. No temporary advancement is worth permanent failure.

In pursuit of that goal, I turn towards Theseus and reach out for his hand. "We must leave, son! Come, quickly!"

She swallows. “This is an important moment. For both of us. I’ll offer you a choice now, the one coherent thing the old man said. Avdol was the last remaining person who knew anything about you in any way that mattered. This... you—we’re free now.” She smiles. “But you have to decide what you want your life to be. If it isn’t with me, then... I think this is your chance to escape everything.”

messages.content:
“Ah.” I say. My heart is beating really fast again. “I... I chose this name, um, initially, to run away. From you.” What am I saying...? “It’s because I was scared, I think. That the enormity of what I felt wasn’t properly conveyed, or understood, or that *I* wasn’t understood. Which is stupid, because that’s what I’ve nominally wanted this entiiiire time. To be invisible. To be dust. For no one to see... for no one to see me.” A moment. “I was afraid I would pull back the curtain and there would be nothing there.”

I take her hands. It feels like the right thing to do, somehow. 

“You asked me, back. Back then. For me to make you love me, in whatever way that entailed.”

“Did it work?” Hopeless! Desperate! Stupid! I’m still holding her hands. They’re small. They’re warm. I hope it worked. I hope it... I need it to have worked.

I think. I couldn't name any specific ones, but it seems likely, and that's reassuring on some level.

I call out. "Theseus...! You don't have to go along with this... you aren't compelled. You are your own person. Everybody needs to learn that at some point. You chose your name, and had it taken from you... and now, you believe that having the life you had decided on ripped away from you as well is a perfectly natural continuation of that. But it doesn't have to be! You can just say no... it's that easy. Trust me."

“Hey, hey. I’m not finished.” Tendrils uncoil themselves from the president’s corpse. No one is altogether too eager to stand against the anomaly who commands power over earth. “Every pep talk has to break you down before it builds you up, yeah?” 

She looks down. “Um, where was I. Right. Punchline.” She gestures incoherently. “By the way, that tangential relevance held by this fucking failure of a leader —”, she kicks his corpse as punctuation. “...wasn’t even actually connected to your homeland in a way that meant anything. He worked on an international endeavor. And before him? It was some other, possibly marginally less pathetic, but substantially more meaningless figurehead. And that’s how it is. How it was. For my many flaws, of which I have very few, aha, I’ve always been an avid reader. So I’ve gone and immersed myself in the lore, here.”

She shakes her head. “When it wasn’t globalism, you were under the boot of the fucking FRENCH.” She stares at Viotto, smirking. “The Ottomans before that. But this isn’t a lost cause, is it? A wellspring of power once flowed — a sprout birthed in the fertile soil this very building is sitting on.”

She stares into the distance. “The terror as the elephants trampled the alps, as living behemoths overtook their homes... everyone vilifies or deifies Rome. messages.content:
Verl smiles.
“A memory is a corpse, and corpses are quite hard to keep moving. I will give them something alive to remember the name of. But I will not do so alone. My own strengths will need to be supplanted by those in this room — by trusted advisors, generals, leaders... all of whom will, of course, be seeing substantial promotions. ...And my partner. Who I need myself.” 
She doesn’t meet his eyes. 
“Divided we fall. But united, I will lead you all to prosperity and the endless growth only an invasive species can manage. ...That last part was a joke.” Verl cackles. “...Sorry, sorry, excuse me. Serious moment.”
There’s murmuring in the room. Much more doubts about this woman being in full command of her faculties, even if fear keeps such slander from escalating into action. Wasn’t this supposed to be a more clear cut transfer of power...? It wasn’t for the girl herself, was it? It was for so-and-so, or a transitional period to restructure the state around the principles and traditional values of what-have-you... was everyone fed a different story...?
Verl shakes her head. “I understand change is frightening. But I’ll be brutally honest. You don’t have much to lose. And I exist... to serve the interests of this country.” She puts her hand to her heart. “I really do have no other home. ...Please clap.”

There’s scattered applause. Motivated by some deranged genuine supporters or fear of someone who may have a hairpin trigger temper or some combination thereof.

Detlef Praxis wanders through the outskirts of the capital province, having evacuated. This is long before anything that takes place after a timeskip, obviously. A guard escorts him. Just a normal one, not guard with a capital G.

“I just… I mean, I get why people like that Wress guy might’ve been upset. It just seems pretty foolish to throw out everything rather than just fix the system we already have. You know? I know Catarina and Zita are both reasonable women. Surely they could’ve simply, uh, talked it out, somehow.”

“…You were the heir, right?” The guard asks.

“Ohoho, no. No, not really. Maybe things would’ve turned out differently. …If I was able to be that.” He sighs. “I just… wish things could go back. Not just to before today. Before… whenever everything went wrong.”

The guard’s eyes widen. She gasps.

“What is it?” Detlef asks.

“It’s… a friend sent me a message through Sending. The Hifele guy...” She covers her beak.

“Holy crap…!”

“A waste of time.” Solnit shakes his head. “It isn’t as though I’ve cut contact with Dextrum. He knows everything I could tell him.”

“And everything I’m willing to disclose.” Isador Dechai smirks slyly, resting a leg on the table in the center of this currently-functioning-as-a-waiting-room. “I imagine it’s more of a matter of finally getting some in-person testimony now that there’s something closer to a functional government around to keep records.” He sighs.

“This selection of people is stupid.” Gratia mutters. She’s alive, it turns out. Wow. No way. “I got nothin’ to say to the feds.”

“You acquiesced to come here, did you not?” Solnit questions, gesturing dramatically within his robe, a newer and more ostentatious outfit than his previous nonsense.

“I thought I could pilfer shit from the venue. You know. Gratia at the Function, what will she do? Hah.”

“True.” Isador.

Solnit doesn’t understand this. “Are you not busy sucking up to Voreverl, or something?”

“Haha, that’s…!” Gratia looks down. “M…maybe eventually. I mean, once I can… when I get over…”
She goes silent.

“Incomprehensible.” Solnit scoffs. “And you? Are you not worried our new king-who-isn’t-calling-himself-that will apprehend you as the criminal you are?”

“Nah, Dexie and I go way back.” Isador mutters.

“Dexie?! I highly doubt that.”

“Well, we ain’t exactly friends. Still haven’t forgiven him for… well, it was my fault as much. Should’ve been able to protect him.”

“Protect… Virtos?”

“No.” Isador doesn’t elaborate, but he’s obviously thinking about his dead brother or whatever. “And you? I guess going AWOL to run a cult hasn’t dampened your need to be his lapdog.”

“It is NOT a cult - merely a society based on principled logical beliefs, and the evident probability of Eulogia’s return - and also I hate him, and I’m here to keep up appearances.”

“Appearances of what?” Isador questions.

“You wouldn’t get it.” Solnit shakes his head.

“Yeah.” Isador doesn’t say anything else.
